    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Phymatopteris longisquamata are derived from its leaves and stems, which are rich in flavonoids and phenolic acids. Infusion and decoction are traditional preparations, made by steeping the plant material in hot water to release its bioactive compounds, which are then consumed as a tea to treat various health issues. Tincture is another preparation, made by extracting the plant's bioactive compounds with a solvent, such as ethanol or glycerin, to create a concentrated liquid that can be taken sublingually or added to water. Salve is a topical preparation, made by infusing the plant material in a carrier oil, such as coconut or olive oil, to create a soothing balm that can be applied to the skin to treat wounds and inflammation. These preparations are used to treat a range of health issues, including fever, cough, and respiratory problems, due to the plant's antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties.",
